---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const allGuides = await getCollection('guides');
const germanyA1Guides = allGuides.filter(g => g.data.category === 'germany-a1');

const jsonLD = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do I need a German A1 certificate for a family reunion visa?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Many spouse and family reunion applicants need to show basic German skills at A1 level, but exceptions and document rules depend on the case. Verify with the German mission or authority handling your application before booking an exam.' }},
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which exams are commonly used for German family reunion A1?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Goethe-Zertifikat A1: Start Deutsch 1 and telc Deutsch A1 are commonly discussed options. Acceptance can depend on the authority, location, certificate version, and your case, so confirm officially before paying.' }},
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Should I start with booking or with the requirement check?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Start with the requirement check. Once you know whether A1 applies and which proof is accepted, compare exam providers, centers, fees, result timing, documents, and retake risk.' }},
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I use VisaLang instead of official sources?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'No. VisaLang is a navigation guide. Use it to organize the route, then verify current requirements, fees, dates, accepted certificates, and document rules with official sources.' }},
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="Germany A1 family reunion: requirements, exam, booking, and documents" description="Germany A1 family reunion route: verify the requirement, choose an exam, check fees and test centres, prepare documents, study, and plan a retake with official sources." jsonLD={jsonLD}>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <article class="guide-article route-hub-page">
        <p class="eyebrow">Germany · Family Reunion</p>
        <h1>Germany A1 for family reunion: complete route guide</h1>
        <p class="guide-summary">If you may need basic German proof for a spouse or family reunion route, start here. This hub organizes the requirement check, exam choice, booking risk, documents, preparation, retake planning, and official verification into one route.</p>

        <div class="guide-trustbar" aria-label="Route decision reminder">
          <span>Quick route answer: confirm whether A1 applies before you compare providers or dates.</span>
          <span>Requirements, exemptions, fees, test centres, and certificate treatment must be checked with current official sources.</span>
        </div>

        <h2>Who should start here</h2>
        <p>Start here if you are planning a German spouse or family-reunion application and have not yet confirmed the language-proof requirement, accepted certificate, or booking timeline. If you already have a written instruction from the responsible mission, use this route to check the practical decisions it creates.</p>

        <h2>Who should verify an exemption first</h2>
        <p>Do not register because an online checklist says “everyone needs A1.” If your route, the person in Germany, your application location, or your circumstances may affect the requirement, take the official mission or authority page as the starting point. This site cannot determine an exemption or outcome for an individual case.</p>

        <h2>Germany A1 route overview</h2>
        <p>Use this page as the Germany A1 route index. It does not replace BAMF, the German mission, Goethe-Institut, telc, or your local test center. It helps you move through the right questions in the right order before you pay for an exam or submit documents.</p>

        <h2>Five core decision guides</h2>
        <p>Use these pages when the route has moved from a general requirement question to a decision you need to make now.</p>
        <div class="guide-related-grid">
          <a class="article-card" href="/guides/goethe-a1-fees-by-country/">
            <p class="card-category">Fees</p>
            <h3>Goethe A1 exam fees: check your local price</h3>
          </a>
          <a class="article-card" href="/guides/goethe-a1-test-centers/">
            <p class="card-category">Test centers</p>
            <h3>Goethe A1 test centers: verify an official exam centre</h3>
          </a>
          <a class="article-card" href="/guides/goethe-a1-retake-policy/">
            <p class="card-category">Retake</p>
            <h3>Goethe A1 retake: plan your next attempt</h3>
          </a>
          <a class="article-card" href="/guides/german-a1-documents-checklist/">
            <p class="card-category">Documents</p>
            <h3>German A1 documents checklist: booking, test day, visa</h3>
          </a>
          <a class="article-card" href="/guides/goethe-a1-speaking-topics/">
            <p class="card-category">Speaking</p>
            <h3>Goethe A1 speaking topics: safe practice plan</h3>
          </a>
        </div>

        <h2>Step 1: Confirm whether A1 applies</h2>
        <p>Many spouse applicants are asked to show basic German at A1 level, but exemptions and document rules depend on the relationship category, the person in Germany, the responsible German mission, and the current rule applied to your case.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Start with the <a href="/guides/german-family-reunion-language-requirement/">German family reunion language requirement</a>.</li>
          <li>If you are unsure, use the <a href="/guides/german-family-reunion-language-requirement/">language requirement guide</a> and <a href="/guides/german-a1-family-reunion-faq/">Germany A1 FAQ</a> as checklists, then verify with the official authority.</li>
          <li>Do not book an exam only because another applicant had the same route. Your responsible authority decides your case.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 2: Choose accepted proof</h2>
        <p>For Germany A1 family reunion planning, the most common comparison is Goethe-Zertifikat A1: Start Deutsch 1 versus telc Deutsch A1. The useful question is not which brand is famous; it is which certificate your authority accepts, which center you can book, and whether the result timing fits your document deadline.</p>
        <p><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-germany-family-reunion/">Start with the Goethe A1 route guide</a>, then compare providers in <a href="/guides/goethe-a1-vs-telc-a1/">Goethe A1 vs telc A1</a>.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Compare Goethe A1 and telc A1</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Confirm accepted proof before comparing centers or fees.</li>
          <li>Check the exact adult A1 certificate name and whether all four skills are covered.</li>
          <li>Compare result timing, retake options, ID rules, cancellation rules, and certificate delivery.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 4: Check fees and official centres</h2>
        <p>Once the accepted proof is clear, move from exam choice to booking risk. Do not assume every center offers the same dates, fees, ID rules, or result timeline.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-booking-mistakes/">Goethe A1 booking mistakes</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-pre-booking-checklist/">Goethe A1 pre-booking checklist</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-test-centers/">Goethe A1 test centers</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-fees-by-country/">Goethe A1 fees by country</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/german-a1-exam-booking-timeline/">German A1 exam booking timeline</a></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 5: Book safely</h2>
        <p>Only book when the exact exam, adult level, centre status, passport name, payment deadline, cancellation rule, result process, and your route requirement align. Keep the official listing, centre reply, payment record, and booking confirmation together.</p>

        <h2>Step 6: Prepare documents</h2>
        <p>Separate exam-day documents from visa-file documents. Your test center controls exam-day ID and booking proof; the German mission or authority controls visa-file requirements.</p>
        <p>Use the <a href="/guides/german-a1-documents-checklist/">German A1 documents checklist</a> after you have selected the accepted exam path.</p>

        <h2>Step 7: Build a study plan</h2>
        <p>Preparation should stay legal and practical: official sample materials, original practice prompts, daily listening, and realistic speaking practice. Do not use leaked questions, copied real exam answers, or any service promising guaranteed passing.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-30-day-study-plan/">30-day Goethe A1 study plan</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-study-plan-working-adults/">Goethe A1 study plan for working adults</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-speaking-topics/">Goethe A1 speaking</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-listening-practice/">Goethe A1 listening</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-official-links-practice-resources/">Official links and practice resources</a></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 8: Plan a retake buffer</h2>
        <p>Retake planning is a timeline and budget risk, not a failure prediction. Check the local center rule before assuming you can retake quickly, retake only one module, or receive a new certificate before your appointment.</p>
        <p><a href="/guides/goethe-a1-retake-policy/">Read the Goethe A1 retake policy guide</a>.</p>

        <h2>Common mistakes across the route</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Starting from a local course advert, old price table, or another applicant’s outcome instead of the current official requirement.</li>
          <li>Choosing the soonest date before checking result delivery, visa timing, and a possible retake.</li>
          <li>Mixing exam-day ID requirements with visa-file document requirements.</li>
          <li>Assuming the well-known provider is automatically accepted without checking the exact certificate and local route.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Do I need German A1 for family reunion?</h3>
        <p>Possibly. Many spouse routes require basic German proof, but exceptions and local document rules matter. Verify your route officially before booking.</p>

        <h3>Is Goethe A1 always better than telc A1?</h3>
        <p>No single answer fits every applicant. The safer choice is the certificate your authority accepts and the center whose date, ID rule, result timing, and certificate process fit your case.</p>

        <h3>Can I rely on fee tables from blogs?</h3>
        <p>No. Fees can change by country and center. Use third-party pages only as planning prompts, then check the official local page before paying.</p>

        <h3>Can I study from real leaked exam questions?</h3>
        <p>No. Use official practice materials and original prompts. Avoid leaked materials, copied answers, and guaranteed-pass claims.</p>

        <p><a href="/guides/german-a1-family-reunion-faq/">Open the full Germany A1 FAQ</a>.</p>

        <h2>All Germany A1 guides</h2>
        <div class="guide-related-grid">
          {germanyA1Guides.map(g => (
            <a href={`/guides/${g.data.slug}/`} class="article-card">
              <h3>{g.data.title}</h3>
              <p class="card-meta">{g.data.description}</p>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>

        <h2>Official verification checklist</h2>
        <p>Before you book or submit documents, verify these with official sources: whether A1 applies to your case; any exemption conditions; which certificate is accepted; the exact local fee, date, and result process; the local centre’s ID and cancellation rules; and the document rule for your appointment.</p>

        <p><a class="primary-action" href="/guides/german-family-reunion-language-requirement/">Start Germany A1 route</a></p>
        <p><a class="secondary-action" href="/contact/">Report an official-source correction or route issue</a></p>

        <section class="official-sources">
          <h2>Official sources</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.goethe.de/en/spr/prf.html">Goethe-Institut German examinations</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.bamf.de/EN/Themen/MigrationAufenthalt/ZuwandererDrittstaaten/Familie/familie-node.html">BAMF — family reunification</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.telc.net/en/language-examinations/certificate-exams/german/start-german1-telc-german-a1/">telc Deutsch A1</a></li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <p class="compliance-line">Fees, dates, requirements, and accepted exams change. Always verify with the official source before booking.</p>
        <p class="last-updated">Last updated: 2026-07-10</p>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
